Title: Unreliable Connection
Win32 Is The Only Stable ABI on Linux
Description:
In ELF format there are two ways of providing a hash table of symbols. DT_HASH
and DT_GNU_HASH. The first one is part of SYSV generic ABI and is
well documented and marked as mandatory. DT_GNU_HASH is a newer, smaller, and
faster replacement that is not documented,
implemented in a few places (Glibc, GNU ld, Musl, LLVM, mold, etc.) and a
subject of a couple of blog posts that I’ve
found. Turns out it also doesn’t provide the same
functionality as DT_HASH. To get the number of symbols you have to completely
parse it.

Title: Process injection: breaking all macOS security layers with a single vulnerability
Description:
If you have created a new macOS app with Xcode 13.2, you may noticed this new method in the template:
- (BOOL)applicationSupportsSecureRestorableState:(NSApplication *)app { return YES; } This was added to the Xcode template to address a process injection vulnerability we reported!
In macOS 12.0.1 Monterey, Apple fixed CVE-2021-30873. This was a process injection vulnerability affecting (essentially) all macOS AppKit-based applications. We reported this vulnerability to Apple, along with methods to use this vulnerability to escape the sandbox, elevate privileges to root and bypass the filesystem restrictions of SIP.
